  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .dcf-wrapper .stats-row { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
    .dcf-wrapper .assumption-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .dcf-wrapper .verdict-card { padding: 32px 20px; }
  }
</style>

<div class="dcf-wrapper">
  <div class="header">
    <div class="header-content">
      <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
      <h1>AEP Intrinsic Value</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of American Electric Power — using disclosed assumptions, operating cash flow adjustments, and one final number.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
    <div class="verdict-card">
      <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
      <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
      <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${safeCurrentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
      <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
        {verdictText}
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
    <div class="stats-row">
      <div class="stat-card">
        <div class="stat-value">${(latestRev / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
        <div class="stat-label">Latest Revenue</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <div class="stat-value">${(latestOpCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
        <div class="stat-label">Operating Cash Flow</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <div class="stat-value">${latestEPS.toFixed(2)}</div>
        <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
        <div class="stat-label">Net Cash (Debt)</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
    <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
    <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model. However, AEP is a regulated utility. Utilities require massive, ongoing capital expenditures (CapEx) to maintain and upgrade the grid, which often results in consistently negative Free Cash Flow (FCF). Running a standard DCF on negative FCF yields meaningless results.</p>
    <p><strong>Adaptation:</strong> We use <strong>Operating Cash Flow (OCF)</strong> as the proxy for cash generation. This acknowledges the cash the core business generates before the heavy, regulatory-mandated infrastructure spending that is typically financed by debt and equity in the utility sector.</p>

    <div class="method-step">
      <div class="step-num">1</div>
      <div class="step-content">
        <h4>Start with Operating Cash Flow</h4>
        <p>AEP generated <strong>${latestOpCash.toLocaleString()} million</strong> in operating cash flow recently. We use this base cash flow instead of the heavily negative FCF (${latestFCF.toLocaleString()}M) caused by intense CapEx requirements.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="method-step">
      <div class="step-num">2</div>
      <div class="step-content">
        <h4>Project growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
        <p>We grow Operating Cash Flow at <strong>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100)}% per year</strong> for 5 years. Regulated utilities have highly predictable, state-approved rate increases, allowing for steady, low-to-mid single-digit growth.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="method-step">
      <div class="step-num">3</div>
      <div class="step-content">
        <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
        <p>After Year 5, we assume growth settles at <strong>{(growthRateTerminal * 100)}% forever</strong>. This aligns with long-term inflation and GDP growth, typical for a mature, regional monopoly utility.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="method-step">
      <div class="step-num">4</div>
      <div class="step-content">
        <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
        <p>Future cash flows are discounted at <strong>{(discountRate * 100)}%</strong>. Utilities are considered "bond proxies" with low volatility (low beta). Given the 10Y Treasury is 4.18%, a 6.5% discount rate provides an appropriate premium for a low-risk utility stock.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="method-step">
      <div class="step-num">5</div>
      <div class="step-content">
        <h4>Subtract net debt, divide by shares</h4>
        <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (which is heavily negative due to utility debt) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding (${latestShares.toLocaleString()}M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
    <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>

    <div class="assumption-grid">
      <div class="assumption-card">
        <div class="label">Op. Cash Flow Growth (Yrs 1-5)</div>
        <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100)}%</div>
        <div class="rationale">
          Utilities grow earnings by expanding their rate base (assets) and having regulators approve rate hikes. AEP targets 5-7% EPS growth. We model a slightly more conservative 4% cash flow growth to account for regulatory lag and potential pushback on customer bills.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="assumption-card">
        <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
        <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
        <div class="rationale">
          10Y Treasury is 4.18%. AEP's beta is typically low (around 0.5-0.6). Using CAPM, a required return of ~6.5% is standard for regulated utilities, reflecting their near-monopoly status and highly predictable cash flows.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="assumption-card">
        <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
        <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100)}%</div>
        <div class="rationale">
          2% represents long-term baseline economic growth and inflation. A utility cannot grow faster than its regional economy forever without infinitely raising rates, so terminal growth must remain modest.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ CASH FLOW PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
    <h2>Projected Cash Flows (Operating)</h2>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
            <th>Cash Flow ($M)</th>
            <th>PV Factor</th>
            <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Base</td>
            <td>${latestOpCash.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>—</td>
          </tr>
          {projectedCashFlows.map(p => (
            <tr>
              <td>Year {p.year}</td>
              <td>${p.cf.toLocaleString()}</td>
              <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
              <td>${p.pvCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
          <tr class="row-total">
            <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
            <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
    <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
            <th>Value ($M)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Year 6 Cash Flow</td>
            <td>${Math.round(cfYear6).toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Terminal Value (CF₆ ÷ (6.5% − 2%))</td>
            <td>${terminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="row-total">
            <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
            <td class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ FINAL CALCULATION ═══ -->
    <h3>Final Valuation</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
            <th>Value ($M)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>PV of Phase 1 Cash Flows</td>
            <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
            <td>${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>= Enterprise Value</td>
            <td>${enterpriseValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>+ Net Cash (Cash − Debt)</td>
            <td style="color: #ef4444;">${netCash.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>= Equity Value</td>
            <td>${equityValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>÷ Shares Outstanding</td>
            <td>{latestShares.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="row-total">
            <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
            <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ HISTORICAL CHARTS ═══ -->
    <h2>Financial Track Record</h2>

    <h3>Revenue ($M)</h3>
    <div class="bar-chart">
      {revHist.map(r => (
        <div class="bar-row">
          <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
          <div class="bar-track">
            {r.value !== null ? (
              <div class="bar-fill revenue" style={`width: ${(r.value / (Math.max(...revHist.map(h => h.value || 0)) || 1)) * 100}%`}>
                ${r.value.toLocaleString()}
              </div>
            ) : (
              <div class="bar-fill revenue" style="width: 0%; color: #5a6a80; background: none; padding-left:0;">N/A</div>
            )}
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <h3>Operating Cash Flow ($M)</h3>
    <div class="bar-chart">
      {opCashHist.map(r => (
        <div class="bar-row">
          <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
          <div class="bar-track">
            {r.value !== null ? (
              <div class="bar-fill fcf" style={`width: ${(r.value / (Math.max(...opCashHist.map(h => h.value || 0)) || 1)) * 100}%`}>
                ${r.value.toLocaleString()}
              </div>
            ) : (
              <div class="bar-fill fcf" style="width: 0%; color: #5a6a80; background: none; padding-left:0;">N/A</div>
            )}
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
    <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
    <p>Because utilities operate with massive debt loads, small changes in the discount rate or growth assumptions can significantly swing the equity value.</p>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table class="sensitivity-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th style="text-align:left">Disc. Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
            {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
              <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100)}%</th>
            ))}
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
            <tr>
              <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
              {row.values.map((v, i) => (
                <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                  ${v}
                </td>
              ))}
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
    <h2>Risks to the Valuation</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Interest Rates:</strong> Utilities are highly sensitive to interest rates. AEP carries ~$49B in debt. If rates stay higher for longer, refinancing that debt becomes more expensive, eating into cash flows and reducing the intrinsic value.</li>
      <li><strong>Regulatory Pushback:</strong> Utility profits rely on public utility commissions approving rate hikes. If regulators restrict rate increases to protect consumers from inflation, AEP's growth will stall.</li>
      <li><strong>Capital Expenditure Needs:</strong> The transition to renewables and grid hardening requires massive, ongoing CapEx. If these costs exceed what regulators allow into the rate base, shareholder value is destroyed.</li>
      <li><strong>Valuation Method Risk:</strong> Using Operating Cash Flow instead of Free Cash Flow inherently ignores the cost of CapEx. While standard for utility analysis, it requires faith that debt markets remain open and affordable.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq">
      <details>
        <summary>Why didn't you use Free Cash Flow?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">Regulated utilities like AEP have huge CapEx requirements to maintain power plants and the grid. This makes their FCF consistently negative. Running a DCF on negative cash flows produces a negative intrinsic value. By using Operating Cash Flow, we value the core business's cash-generation ability before the mandated infrastructure spending.</div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why is the discount rate so low (6.5%)?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">Utilities are monopolies with highly predictable, state-regulated revenue. This makes them significantly less risky than standard corporations. A lower risk profile dictates a lower required rate of return (discount rate).</div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Does this include the dividend?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">Yes, intrinsically. A DCF values the total cash flow generated by the business. Whether the company pays that cash out as a dividend, uses it to pay down debt, or reinvests it, the total value of the firm is captured in the discounted cash flows.</div>
      </details>
    </div>

